That's right!  The zone of ossification marks bone formation (darker pink stain). BVs from diaphyses penetrate into the calcified cartilage.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

ZR zone of reserve / zone of resting cartilage
chondrocytes quiescent, relatively random
anchors the epiphyseal plate to the epiphysis
ZP zone of proliferation
chondrocytes in rapid cell cycle
form lines of flattened chondrocytes
ZH zone of cell maturation and hypertrophy 
rate of division slows, volume of cytoplasm increases
Interstitial growth of cartilage occurs in the ZP and ZH
ZC zone of calcifying cartilage
chondrocytes die, matrix calcifies
ZO zone of ossification
endochondral bone formation
BVs, osteoclasts from diaphysis penetrate calcified cartilage, rendering lacunae confluent
osteoblasts deposit bone on remains of calcified cartilage
